comment.narrative:
Output 1: 2 Automated weather stations (AWS); 10-day weather agrometeo forecasts, and phenological forecasts of the main agricultural crops, and seasonal forecasts on rivers’ runoff availability for irrigation; 2 Modules on water efficient irrigation technologies; 100 stakeholders trained; 1 new research on climate change in Batken; 
Output 2: Min 9 sites with installed water-efficient irrigation technologies; min 3 rehabilitated and protected of on-farm irrigation facilities; 
Output 3: Minimum 2 publications in press and 3 in social media and 1 TV program

Output 1: 2 Automated weather stations (AWS); 10-day weather agrometeo forecasts, and phenological forecasts of the main agricultural crops, and seasonal forecasts on rives’ runoff availability for irrigation; 2 Modules on water efficient irrigation technologies; 240 stakeholders trained; 2 new research on climate change in Batken; 
Output 2: Min 15 sites with installed water-efficient irrigation technologies; min 7 rehabilitated and protected of on-farm irrigation facilities; 
Output 3: Minimum 2 publications in press and 3 in social media and 1 TV program

Output 1: 
1.1. Project selected and agreed with national partners of the location of automated meteorological stations (AMS), received authorization documents for land plots, technical specifications for the AMS procurement were developed and approved. Currently, the only delay in the full completion of the Project is the acquisition and commissioning of the four automatic weather stations (AMS). This is because in accordance with the Kyrgyzhydromet request for the unification of all AMSs supplied by different donors for the integration into a unified meteorological network, UNDP, in agreement with national partners, used the direct procurement method based on the results of a previous tender financed by the World Bank project (which also supports the unified AMS network).In principle, this approach allows for the standardization and further facilitation of maintenance of similar equipment of the national system AMSs. This also allows the Project to avoid additional actions associated with the subsequent national standardization and certification of the purchased equipment, including its software, which will be provided within the World Bank project.
However, unfortunately, the direct procurement process took longer than originally planned due to the changes made by the supplier to the World Bank contract during its implementation. The delivery and installation of the four AWSs within the Project is possible and envisaged during 2021 – 2022. Due to these circumstances, the extension of the Project for 12 months will not require additional funding;
1.2. Based on the results of consultations with farming communities and Kyrgyzhydromet staff, as part of the implementation of measures to improve climate information products transmitted to farming communities, a comprehensive work completed to build the capacity of Kyrgyzhydromet staff by Roshydromet in the development of agrometeorological products and agrometeorological forecasting, focusing on the following main aspects: 1) adaptation and introduction of a dynamic-statistical method for forecasting the yield of rice of Batken, Osh and Djalal-Abad of Kyrgyzstan; 2) development of an information and forecasting system for operational agrometeorological services; 3) conducting training for specialists of Kyrgyzhydromet in September, 2021 on the use of the introduced agrometeorological dynamic-statistical forecasting methods and information-forecasting system for informing farmers in target areas; 
1.3. Kyrgyzhydromet with support of PhD Ms. Pigolcina from Federal State Budget Body “Main Geophisical Obsrevation named by Voieikov”, finalized and presented the “Agroclimatic reference book in Batken Province”. The main purpose of the reference book is to provide agrometeorological specialists and agricultural workers with agro-climatic materials necessary for their practical work. The project edited and translated the reference book on Kyrgyz language and disseminate it on local and national levels during September 2021;
1.4. Project conducted a detailed assessment of the capacity of local self-government bodies (LSGs) and the Water Users Association (WUA), as well as other stakeholders that may be based in pilot communities of Batken oblast. To increase the knowledge of the farmers on climate smart irrigation, training was developed and carried out using training materials on the use of agroclimatic information, preparedness for various hydroclimatic events, effective approaches to irrigation in the region with low humidity. Based on the assessment, a multi-modular curriculum was developed and implemented to enhance knowledge and skills related to adaptation to climate change, including weather observation and interpretation of agrometeorological forecast, disaster risk reduction, the promotion of climate-smart agriculture, and rational use of water resources for pilot local communities in Batken province. Trainings covered 314 beneficiaries in Batken province. 
1.5. Project prepared of two studies, Climate Change and Food Security: Case Studies in Batken Province to determine how climate change affects food security and agriculture, with recommendations for appropriate actions to reduce the adverse impact of climate change on food security and agriculture in Batken province and “Climate Change and Gender in Batken Province for subsequent elimination of barriers that prevent women in general and women farmers from benefiting from innovative climate change adaptation measures. In September, 2021 the project these two studies edited, translated on Kyrgyz Language, and presented on Batken province level with invitation of national relevant bodies. 
Ouput 2: 
 2.1. In 2020 selection of pilot communities and priority areas of their development is based on a comprehensive socio-economic analysis of the region, a study of local characteristics, analysis of problems, local comparative advantages and opportunities for development. In cooperation with national partners (Heads of pilot LSGs of Batken oblast, WUAs directors, local farm households) and UNDP, the survey was conducted among 92 potential beneficiaries to participate in the project to introduce water-saving technologies. They recommended 77 pilot sites. The project contributed to the process of introduction of the smart irrigation on the land plots of farmers (Aksuu, Alga, Kulundu, Markaz, Orozbekov, Samarkandek and Tort Gul LSGs), in particular, drip irrigation systems (DIS) on a practical example and for further dissemination. DIS systems are already in use by farmers. In 2020-2021, drip irrigation systems were installed on 114 hectares of land for 364 farmers (210 man and 163 women). Potential water savings on the rehabilitated site will amount to 420.568 cubic meters. The total cost of the activities amounted to 14,798,511 Soms, of which 40% is the contribution of farmers and the remaining 60% was covered by the Project;
2.2. Seven objects of on-farm irrigation systems were rehabilitated and protected. The project contributed to a high-quality, detailed analysis of disaster risks with specific indicators of identification of natural, anthropogenic hazards, including projects in the water resources management and environmental safety sectors in cooperation with district and regional departments of the Ministry of Emergency Situations. The most dangerous zones requiring an urgent solution were included in the emergency response plans of the territorial units of the Ministry of Emergency Situations of the pilot districts of the Batken province, which implies their mandatory implementation. It also contributed to the development of mechanisms and tools to address the issues identified as a result of the study in pilot villages and focused more on the implementation of mudflow protection facilities. According to preliminary calculations, the restoration and protection of these facilities avoid losses of about 8,000 cubic meters of irrigation water per season (contribution to SDG 6.4), increase water availability of about 6,500 hectares of irrigated land (contribution to SDG 13.1 and SDG 11.5), and protect about 5,000 hectares of agricultural land from hydrological emergencies (contribution to SDG 13.1 and SDG 11.5). 30,513 beneficiaries (14,841 men, 15,672 women) benefit from the designed mudflow protection measures aimed at increasing employment opportunities, access to water and land production resources, and markets at the local and regional levels. The total costs invested in the rehabilitation of irrigation systems and mudflow protection facilities was 179,088.43 US dollars, of which 4% was the contribution of WUAs, 13% was the contribution of LSGs, 64% was the contribution of the UNDP-TFD Project and 19% was the contribution of UN WFP provision of food (fortified flour and fortified vegetable oil) to project participants from socially vulnerable groups of the population.
