The national consultant and company completed producing the video -course on DIS for future usage by Water Users Associations on national level (link on video course https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z5SAf1uy7B8 ). Meantime three studies edited and presented for wide audience in September 2021

Output 1: 2 Automated weather stations (AWS); 10-day weather agrometeo forecasts, and phenological forecasts of the main agricultural crops, and seasonal forecasts on rives’ runoff availability for irrigation; 2 Modules on water efficient irrigation technologies; 240 stakeholders trained; 2 new research on climate change in Batken; 
Output 2: Min 15 sites with installed water-efficient irrigation technologies; min 7 rehabilitated and protected of on-farm irrigation facilities; 
Output 3: Minimum 2 publications in press and 3 in social media and 1 TV program

Output 1: 

- In agreement with the beneficiary Standardization for direct procurement of Automated meteorological stations was initiated. Installation sites and ToR with technical specifications have been approved by the KyrgyzHydromet. UNDP-RTF Project will increase the density of the observation network up to 60%. Support to Kyrgyzhydromet in the development of a methodology for the development of a Handbook on agroclimatic resources was provided through the Experts Ondemand platform. A Consultant from the Federal State Budgetary Institution “Main Geophysical Observatory named after A.I. Voeikov” was hired;

- Studies on Climate Change and Food Security: Case Studies in Batken province and Climate change and gender in Batken province were initiated. The development of the Terms of Reference was coordinated with the WFP project on food security related issues and with the aim of following up on research recommendations under their future activities;

- LOA is being signed with the Russian National Research Institute of Agricultural Meteorology for development of Information forecasting system for rice and capacity building of KyrgyzHydromet to produce agrometeo forecasts, and phenological forecasts of the main agricultural crops, and seasonal forecasts; 

- Based on a training needs assessment and FAOs experience and expertise multi-module training programme on water efficient irrigation technologies, disaster risks management and climate change issues was developed and trainings are underway in Batken province. FAO in the Kyrgyz Republic has offered advisory support in the design and implementation of a multi-module curriculum. 

Output 2: 

- Seven most climate change vulnerable communities were identified: AA Tort-Gul and Samarkandek of Batken district, AA Aksuu and AA Kulundu of Leilek district, AA Alga, Markaz and Orozbekov of Kadamjai district. 92 potential beneficiaries were questioned, including 8 women. The commission nominated 60 sites for the installation of drip irrigation systems (Batken district: 4 in Tort-Gulskiy AA, 8 in Samarkandek AA; Leilek region: 15 in Aksuu AA, 5 in Kulundu AA; Kadamzhai district: 8 in Alga AA, 5 in Markaz AA, 7 in Orozbekov AA). Based on the results of the technical assessment, 40 sites were final selected for the installation of drip irrigation systems. 40 farmers received drip irrigation systems on their land plots 

- Drip irrigation systems installed on 82 hectares of land and under use. Potential water savings in the rehabilitated lands will be 284.879 cubic meters. The total cost of the activities made 11,802,620 Soms, of which 45% is the contribution of the farmers and the remaining 55% was covered by the Project. Farmers received additional trainings as part of the multi-module trainings;

- Based on the vulnerability assessment of local communities, facilities of irrigation infrastructure vulnerable to hydrological disasters were identified in Batken, Kadamjai and Leilek districts of Batken Province. Agreements have been signed with 7 LSGs most vulnerable to climate change: AA Tort-Gul and Samarkandek of Batken district, AA Aksuu and Kulundu of Leilek district, AA Alga, Markaz and Orozbekov of Kadamjai district for the implementation of relevant activities, using the HACT modality. The works on the rehabilitation of canals and protective structures were carried out by the LSGs themselves together with the WUA - which increased the sense of ownership and succession of results.The rehabilitation and protection of these facilities will avoid the loss of 8,000 cubic meters of irrigation water per season, increase the water availability for 6,500 hectares of irrigated land and protect 5,000 hectares of agricultural land from hydrological emergencies. 30,513 beneficiaries (men -14,841, women -15,672) will benefit from the projected mudflow protection measures. The WFP project has contributed via the Food for Work program by paying for the manpower of local communities in the form of food - flour and butter worth US $ 34,746 and is interested in scaling up the results of the project. Jointly with the Ministry of Emergency Situations a mudflow section of Zhayilmasai was rehabilitated, with the laying of 210 gabions, through local funding. With the State Agency for Environmental Protection and Forestry it is planned to work on bioengineering activities to strengthen slopes of canals in 2021;

Output 3: 

- A special working group has been created under the Kyrgyzhydromet to support the project implementation.

- The Project has contributed to the initiative on improvement of waste management at Lenin Peak, with the participation of local communities from Batken province. These activities will also add value to the COVID-19 response in the tourism sector hard hit by the pandemic. By working to clean up and transport trash in the Lenin Peak area, local service providers (porters, mountain guides, and others) have gained employment opportunities during the extremely challenging 2020 summer tourist season.

- Communication strategy was developed as part of AWP as well as Gender Mainstreaming Plan. Within the Indicator 1.4. work on the preparation of the study “Climate Change and Gender in Batken Oblast” in underway.

- Short videos in three languages were prepared on Rehabilitation of on-farm canals; Drip irrigation systems; Automatic weather stations;

Output 1: Four Automated weather stations (AWS) are in place 
Output 2: Min 7 sites with installed water-efficient irrigation technologies; min 2 rehabilitated and protected of on-farm irrigation facilities; 
Output 3: Minimum 2 publications in press and 1 in social media
